[    9s] |From nobody Tue Jul  4 10:54:31 2006
[    9s] |From: Aharon Robbins <arnold@skeeve.com>
[    9s] |Subject: Re: /dev/fd/n bug in gawk 3.1.5
[    9s] |To: aschorr@telemetry-investments.com
[    9s] |Cc: Juergen.Kahrs@vr-web.de, bug-gawk@gnu.org, spcecdt@armory.com
[    9s] |Date: Tue, 04 Jul 2006 07:40:10 +0300
[    9s] |
[    9s] |> Date: Mon, 03 Jul 2006 16:54:19 -0400
[    9s] |> From: "Andrew J. Schorr" <aschorr@telemetry-investments.com>
[    9s] |> Subject: Re: /dev/fd/n bug in gawk 3.1.5
[    9s] |> To: Aharon Robbins <arnold@skeeve.com>
[    9s] |>
[    9s] |> Hi,
[    9s] |>
[    9s] |> Note that the pid test was failing silently: "make check" was
[    9s] |> reporting "ALL TESTS PASSED" even though gawk was SEGV'ing
[    9s] |> in the pid test.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |I noticed this on RHEL 4 system at work where the test failed
[    9s] |noisily. I'm guessing a difference in versions of bash...
[    9s] |
[    9s] |> Attached is a patch to the pid test
[    9s] |> that fixes this problem (i.e. the test will now fail noisily).
[    9s] |> The problem was that the SEGV was aborting the script
[    9s] |> prematurely, and leaving a zero-length output file, which was
[    9s] |> precisely correct.  The fix was to make sure that test/pid.awk
[    9s] |> produces some output.  That way we get a comparison failure
[    9s] |> if the output file is empty.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |Actually, the correct fix is to keep gawk from SEGV-ing in the
[    9s] |first place. Below is full diff of io.c relative to 3.1.5.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |I will probably incorporate your changes also as extra insurance.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |Thanks,
[    9s] |
[    9s] |Arnold
[    9s] |-----------------------------------------------------
[    9s] |Mon Jul  3 00:27:59 2006  Arnold D. Robbins  <arnold@skeeve.com>
[    9s] |
[    9s] |	* io.c (INTERNAL_HANDLE): New constant for use by `iop_alloc'
[    9s] |	when allocating an internal IOBUF.
[    9s] |	(pidopen, useropen): Use it.
[    9s] |	(iop_alloc): Add check for it and just return iop.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |Sun Jun 18 22:27:25 2006  Arnold D. Robbins  <arnold@skeeve.com>
[    9s] |
[    9s] |	Repair internal names like /dev/user, /dev/pid, as well as /dev/fd/N,
[    9s] |	which have been broken for a long time but noone noticed.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |	* io.c (is_internal): new macro to check for internal file like `/dev/user'.
[    9s] |	(spec_setup): Reduce to two parameters, allocate logic is always true.
[    9s] |	Add IOP_NO_FREE to flag.
[    9s] |	(pidopen, useropen): Return `IOBUF *' instead of int. Fix
[    9s] |	logic to test if `iop' parameter is NULL and if so to allocate it.
[    9s] |	(specfdopen,): Return `IOBUF *' instead of int. Fix
[    9s] |	logic to test if `iop' parameter is NULL and if so to allocate it.
[    9s] |	Don't set IOP_NO_FREE in flag.
[    9s] |	(iop_open): Remove `IOBUF iob' field from `struct internal' and its use
[    9s] |	and the use of `spec_setup' from the code here. Change the check in the
[    9s] |	call to the open function to look for NULL.
[    9s] |	(get_a_record): Use `is_internal' in initial check for filling the
[    9s] |	buffer to not try to call `read' on internal files. If true, set
[    9s] |	the IOP_AT_EOF in the flag and return EOF.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |Fri Aug 12 13:10:33 2005  Arnold D. Robbins  <arnold@skeeve.com>
[    9s] |
[    9s] |	* io.c (iop_alloc): Only free `iop' if it was malloc'ed in
[    9s] |	the first place.
[    9s] |
[    9s] |--- ../gawk-3.1.5/io.c	2005-07-26 21:07:43.000000000 +0300
[    9s] |+++ io.c	2006-07-03 00:27:51.000000000 +0300
